## DIAGNOSTIC SESSION
Step 1: Info: Patient presents with extreme fatigue, jaundice (yellow skin), and an elevated alanine aminotransferase (ALT) level. | Uncertainties: Acute viral hepatitis (A, B, C): common cause of marked ALT elevation with fatigue and jaundice; Drug-induced liver injury (e.g., acetaminophen, herbal supplements, antibiotics): can cause high ALT and jaundice depending on exposure; Alcoholic hepatitis: can present with jaundice and fatigue—AST often > ALT but still possible; Obstructive cholestasis (biliary obstruction, choledocholithiasis, or cholestatic tumors): produces jaundice—ALT may be elevated but alkaline phosphatase and bilirubin patterns may help differentiate. | Action: REQUEST TEST: Vital Signs | Reason: Vital signs (BP, HR, temperature, RR, SpO2) and immediate hemodynamic data are essential early information to assess severity (fever suggests infectious/viral etiology, hypotension or tachycardia suggests systemic illness or severe liver dysfunction) and will guide urgency and next diagnostic steps.
Step 2: Info: Vital signs: Temperature 37.9°C (100.2°F) — low-grade fever; Blood pressure 100/74 mmHg; Heart rate 72 bpm; Respiratory rate 14/min. | Uncertainties: Acute viral hepatitis (fever, fatigue, jaundice, elevated ALT): under consideration; Drug-induced liver injury (e.g., acetaminophen or antibiotics causing marked ALT elevation and jaundice): under consideration; Alcoholic hepatitis (history of heavy alcohol use: under consideration; typically AST>ALT but can present with jaundice and fatigue): under consideration; Obstructive/cholestatic process (e.g., choledocholithiasis or cholangitis — jaundice and fever possible, but ALT may be variably elevated).: under consideration | Action: ASK PATIENT: What is your age and sex? | Reason: Patient demographics (age and sex) are essential early data that influence pretest probability of causes (e.g., pregnancy-related liver disease, autoimmune hepatitis in young women, alcoholic vs. metabolic etiologies) and guide which tests to prioritize.
Step 3: Info: 25-year-old male; Vital signs: T 37.9°C, BP 100/74 mmHg, HR 72 bpm, RR 14; Presenting complaints: extreme fatigue and jaundice (yellow skin); Noted elevated alanine aminotransferase (ALT) previously. | Uncertainties: Acute viral hepatitis (A/B/C): Typical presentation with fatigue, jaundice, and elevated ALT in a young adult; Acetaminophen or other toxin-induced acute liver injury: Common cause of marked ALT elevation and hepatic dysfunction — requires medication/overdose history; Obstructive/cholestatic process (e.g., biliary obstruction): Can cause jaundice though usually with higher alkaline phosphatase and conjugated bilirubin — needs differentiation from hepatocellular injury. | Action: REQUEST TEST: Hepatic panel (AST, ALT, total and direct bilirubin, alkaline phosphatase, albumin) and PT/INR | Reason: These tests will determine whether the pattern is hepatocellular (high AST/ALT) versus cholestatic (high ALP, conjugated bilirubin), assess severity and synthetic liver function (albumin, PT/INR), and guide next steps (hepatitis serologies, acetaminophen level, imaging).
Step 4: Info: Hepatic panel shows isolated marked ALT elevation: ALT 2,000 IU/L; AST, total/direct bilirubin, alkaline phosphatase, albumin, and PT/INR are all within normal limits. | Uncertainties: Acetaminophen toxicity: extremely high ALT is characteristic and requires urgent treatment; Acute viral hepatitis (HAV, HBV, HCV, EBV, CMV): can cause marked ALT elevations though typically AST also elevated and bilirubin may rise; Autoimmune hepatitis: can present with high ALT in young patients though more common in females; Muscle injury/rhabdomyolysis: can raise ALT (and CK) and may explain isolated ALT elevation. | Action: REQUEST TEST: Serum acetaminophen level | Reason: A very high ALT (≈2,000) is a classic presentation of acetaminophen-induced hepatotoxicity, which requires prompt diagnosis because N-acetylcysteine is time-sensitive; obtaining a serum acetaminophen level immediately will differentiate this urgent, treatable cause from viral/autoimmune or muscle-related causes and guide emergent management.
Step 5: Info: Serum acetaminophen level: normal. | Uncertainties: Acute viral hepatitis (A/B/C): can cause marked ALT elevation and fever/jaundice; Drug-induced liver injury (non-acetaminophen): many drugs/herbals cause isolated hepatocellular injury with very high ALT; Autoimmune hepatitis: can present with very high ALT in young adults; Ischemic/vascular ('shock liver'): typically causes massive transaminase rise but usually with hypotension—less likely given current vitals. | Action: REQUEST TEST: Viral hepatitis serologies (HAV IgM, HBsAg and IgM anti-HBc, HCV antibody and HCV RNA) | Reason: Viral hepatitis (especially A and B) is a leading cause of very high ALT with fever/jaundice; serologies/RNA will rapidly differentiate viral causes from drug-induced or autoimmune etiologies and guide urgent management.
