Step 1: Info: Presentation: newborn with feeding intolerance and bilious (green) vomiting. | Uncertainties: Malrotation with midgut volvulus: classically causes sudden bilious vomiting and can lead to ischemia/shock; urgent to exclude. Duodenal atresia/obstruction (including annular pancreas): causes bilious (or non-bilious) vomiting soon after feeds, may have double bubble on imaging. Jejunoileal atresia or small bowel obstruction: presents with bilious vomiting and abdominal distension; may have delayed meconium passage. Meconium ileus (CF): can present with neonatal obstruction and bilious vomiting, often with failure to pass meconium and inspissated meconium on imaging. | Action: REQUEST TEST: Vital Signs | Reason: Obtain immediate assessment of cardiopulmonary stability (HR, BP, RR, Temp, SpO2) to determine urgency of resuscitation/transfer and to identify signs of shock or sepsis that would prioritize emergent surgical evaluation (e.g., volvulus). Vital signs are early critical data per clinical best practices.
